  <details>
    <summary>What's Ethereum?</summary>
    <img src="http://danfinlay.com/why-leaving-apple/img/ethereum.png">
    <p>Ethereum is a <a href="https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turing_complete">turing-complete</a> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_chain_(database)">blockchain</a> as described by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vitalik_Buterin">Vitalik Buterin</a> in this <a href="https://github.com/ethereum/wiki/wiki/White-Paper">whitepaper</a>. Apparently <a href="http://www.wired.com/2014/01/ethereum/">Wired did an article on it.</a></p>
    <p>What this means is Ethereum is a computer that runs in a completely distributed, public space.</p>
    <p>Users can write anything from a simple script, like a monthly rent payment, to anything they can imagine, even something as complicated as <a href="http://boardroom.to/">a democratic organization</a></p>
    <p>Unlike normal web sites or applications, no central authority owns the communications.</p>
    <p>No one can censor posts on an Ethereum app, unless that app explicitly makes that legal.</p>
    <p>Anyone can read the source code for an Ethereum app, they run in public always.</p>
    <p>Ethereum applications do not require any extra infrastructure. Once they are live, they continue to live on their own, on the collective blockchain.</p>
    <p>It's hard to capture the full implications here.</p>
